 and translations of Latin and Greek texts, early modern mythographies and the medieval tradition of Troy. They attend to Heywood’s thought-provoking imitations and juxtapositions of these sources, his use of myth to interrogate gender and heroism, and his turn to antiquity to celebrate and defamiliarise the theatrical or political present. Heywood’s better-known works are discussed alongside critically neglected ones, making the collection valuable for undergraduates and researchers alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aClassical literaturexAppreciationzEnglandxHistory. 4aShakespeare 2021. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aThomas Heywood.  aclassical antiquity.  aclassical reception.  aearly modern drama.  agenre.  ahumanism.  aintertextuality.  amyth / classical tradition.  amythography.  awomen.1 aCoffin, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemetriou, Tania, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemetriou, Tania, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHeavey, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeyré, Yves, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPollard, Tanya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPreedy, Chloe Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRowland, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStapleton, M. L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTemple, Camilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aValls-Russell, Janice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aValls-Russell, Janice, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.go